Good catch! You're absolutely right. Because you have process-unmapped-keys yes in your defcfg, Kanata "sees" every key on your keyboard even if it isn't explicitly listed in defsrc or deflayer.

However, there is a subtle but critical technical distinction in how tap-hold-release-keys works with unmapped keys:

The "Unmapped" Catch
When you use tap-hold-release-keys, Kanata looks for the aliases or keycodes defined in your defvar lists.

Mapped Keys: If you press u, Kanata knows exactly what that is because it's in your defsrc. The guardrail triggers instantly.

Unmapped Keys: If you press a key not in defsrc (like p or 7), Kanata still "sees" it because of process-unmapped-keys, but it treats it as an external event.

In some versions of Kanata, tap-hold-release-keys may not reliably "intercept" an unmapped key to trigger the hold-action of a mapped key. To ensure the guardrails are bulletproof, it is best practice to include any key you intend to use as a "trigger" inside the defsrc, even if you just pass it through with _ in your layers.

Updated Strategy
Since you prefer a tidy syntax, we can keep the defsrc minimal, but I've expanded the defvar lists to include the standard keycodes. Even if they aren't in defsrc, listing them in the variable tells the alias: "If you see this keycode happen anywhere on the system, trigger the modifier."

